{
  "doc_id": "17834",
  "text": "Diagnosis of appendicitis is made mainly by history and physical examination, and laboratory study and radiologic investigation are helpful in equivocal cases. Clinical presentation has overall sensitivity and specificity of 45-81% and 36-53% [CITATION_1] , respectively. The possible cause is variation of appendix [CITATION_2] . With regard to laboratory study, an increase in white blood cell count (WBC), predominance of polymorphonuclear leukocytes (PMN), and increased C-reactive protein (CRP) levels were associated with the risk and severity of complications in appendicitis [CITATION_3] . With elderly patients, the diagnosis is more difficult, and this can lead to higher mortality and morbidity rates than in the general population.",
